@flexiarg equity/shared-maintenance
@title Local Adaptation Without Stewardship Fragments the Commons
@keywords stewardship, materials, commons, maintenance, licensing, curation, NPT, Ostrom, co-evolution, learning
@audience programme designers, community coordinators, futon coordination layer
@tone analytic-foundational
@style pattern
@references [equity/ARGUMENT equity/protected-interaction equity/contribution-pathways]

! conclusion: Materials stay current and trusted only when stewardship is distributed across a contributor community with open licensing, a shared repository, and a light-touch curation process. Without stewardship, local learning fragments and the whole system cannot learn from its own variation.
  + context: A programme provides high-quality materials that are praised by trainers but that age, require local adaptation, and cannot easily be upstreamed. In NPT terms this is Collective Action (3.2 Relational Integration, 3.4 Contextual Integration): the work of maintaining connections between the materials, the trainers, and the programme. In Ostrom's terms this is knowledge-commons stewardship. In the whole-board-play analogy, Patterns 1-2 gave the agent the rules and the conditions to play; this pattern asks whether what the agent learns from playing can flow back into the system that shapes future play.
  + IF:
    Trainers are developing local competence through iterative delivery (Pattern 2). Each local adaptation is a learning event: the trainer discovers what works in their setting, what doesn't, what needs to be added or removed. These local adaptations are the system's equivalent of the internal representations that develop during whole-board play — local structure that responds to local conditions, discovered through interaction rather than specified centrally.
  + HOWEVER:
    There is no mechanism to upstream local improvements. Each trainer reworks materials independently. Adaptations stay local — the system's local learning never propagates. The "gold standard" reputation erodes as content drifts from practice. Maintenance falls to whoever happens to notice a problem — invisible labour on top of already constrained time. Open licensing was planned but the stewardship infrastructure was not built. This is like AlphaZero playing millions of games but never updating its weights: the games happen, local information is generated, but nothing flows backward into the shared structure.
  + THEN:
    The programme establishes open licensing and a shared repository with a light-touch curation process. Contributing an adaptation is made as easy as consuming a resource. Local groups catalogue assets, a community of practice shares adaptations, and training partners review and update the syllabus. The shift is from individual burden to community infrastructure. Crucially, the upstream pathway is not just for materials — it is the mechanism through which the programme learns from its own local variation. Each adaptation that reaches the shared repository refines the commons, making it a better conversion factor for future trainers.
  + BECAUSE:
    Sen: Usable materials are part of the ongoing conditions that sustain capability beyond the initial event. But capability is not static — it develops through use. When a trainer adapts materials, they are developing both their own competence and a local variant that may be better suited to a class of settings. If that variant cannot flow back, the capability gain is private and the commons degrades.

    Whole-board play: The backward propagation of local learning into shared structure is what makes the difference between a system that learns and a system that merely runs. AlphaZero's power comes not from any single game but from the fact that what is learned in each game updates the weights that shape future games. In the training programme, the "weights" are the shared materials, the syllabus, the accumulated practical knowledge of what works. Without an upstream pathway, local games are played but the system's weights never update. The resource and its users must develop together — that is the co-evolutionary logic.

    Ostrom: This is knowledge-commons stewardship: maintenance, adaptation, and reuse depend on shared rules and contributor roles. Open licensing enables sharing; it does not produce stewardship. The curation process and contributor roles must be designed alongside the repository. The shift from individual burden to community infrastructure marks the transition toward architecture-level coordination.
  + NEXT-STEPS:
    - Establish open licensing with an explicit upstream pathway
    - Define the curation process: who reviews, who accepts, what the cadence is
    - Make contributing as easy as consuming — the friction gradient should favour upstream flow
    - Test: can a local adaptation reach the shared repository within one cycle?
    - This requires a contributor community (medium-high coordination) and should be resolved after conditions 1-2
  + INVARIANT-STATEMENT:
    Local adaptations can flow back into the shared resource through a defined curation process. The materials commons has at least one active steward beyond the original author. The upstream pathway is no harder to use than the downstream consumption pathway.
  + FAILURE-MODES:
    - No backward propagation: local learning stays local, the system's weights never update
    - Content drift: materials diverge from practice without systematic review
    - Invisible labour: maintenance is unrecognised work that compounds trainer overload
    - Ad hoc sharing: "a couple of colleagues have uploaded their slides" — unsystematic, fragile
    - Licensing without stewardship: open licence exists but no one curates, reviews, or upstreams
  + ANCESTORS:
    - UKRN T3 transcript evidence: T1 ("a gold standard of how to run an intro to reproducible research session")
    - UKRN T3 transcript evidence: T1 ("a couple of colleagues have uploaded their slides")
    - REDF proposal: explicitly planned permissive licensing and materials "made available to all for use/reuse"
  + DERIVATION:
    Derived from NPT Collective Action (3.2, 3.4) via the UKRN T3 analysis.
    Mapped to the equity loop at capability→contribution: local capability that fragments instead of feeding back.
    Deepened via whole-board play: the backward propagation of local learning into shared structure is what makes a system that learns rather than a system that merely runs.
    Ostrom: knowledge-commons stewardship requires shared rules and contributor roles.
    Coordination requirement: Medium-high (community).
